## 8. Interpretation

This run should be regarded as a broad operational failure under the current framework.

### 8.1 What the results support

- the benchmark is exposing a serious yaw generalisation problem
- distance is still usable for much of the distribution
- distance failures are not randomly distributed; near range and crop-boundary cases are important
- near-180° orientation confusion is present and measurable
- the JSON output is sufficient to construct exact metric-defined failure categories

### 8.2 What remains unresolved

- whether the broad yaw degradation is caused by model capacity, training data, target representation, checkpoint selection, or preprocessing mismatch
- whether close-range/lower-frame failures are primarily visual ambiguity, scale sensitivity, crop composition, or label distribution
- whether the most severe distance failures are caused by padding/crop handling, ROI localisation, training coverage, or a model extrapolation issue at image boundaries
- which samples should receive **F7** visually ambiguous / hard-case tags

The development story for this run is therefore different from the earlier analysed report. The relevant question is not how to trim a sparse residual tail. The priority is to explain why the yaw distribution has shifted beyond the operational threshold for most samples.

